        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The line widths of the SiO J=2-1 (v=3) emission detected in NGC 1068 are only several km/s, which require a velocity resolution of similar or even less than 1 km/s. On the other hand, the total velocity range of NGC 1068 is several hundreds of km/s, which needs to be coverd by a bandwidth of 234.375 MHz at this frequency. So to cover the spectral windows of the SiO lines, we need a bandwidth of 234.375 MHz and a frequency resolution of 244.141 kHz. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We prefer to have the best angular resolution (~0.1") to resolve the SiO and CH3OH emission, with an expected seperation of about 0.3". With such a resolution, we can also measure the kinematics of the SiO maser in the circum-nuclear region to study the properties of the central supermassive black hole. But if the high resolution observation is too difficult to be done, observations with  a resolution of about 0.3" is also acceptable, which can confirm the discovery of the new types of mega-masers and study the origin of them in NGC 1068.  Because we do not expect much extended emission from such masers, we will not have special requirement for the short baseline coverage for this project.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The peak of the SiO J=2-1 (v=3) emission in NGC 1068 detected with IRAM 30m is about 20 mJy, at two velocities with line widths of several km/s. So a velocity resolution of better than 1 km/s is required for this observation. Since the SiO emission may be resolved to several beams by ALMA for each velocity component, we need to archive an rms level to better than 2 mJy/beam for 5 sigma detections if the SiO emission at one velocity is extended to 2 beams.  We choose a velocity resolution of about 0.85 km/s, and thus, we need 4 hours observing time, including the overheads, to reach an rms of 1.8 mJy/beam. The CH3OH emission is broader but with a lower peak intensity (~6mJy). We will smooth the velocity resolution to about 10 km/s for the CH3OH emission, which can reach similar signal to noise ratios to that for SiO.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
